issue_body:
In draft-ietf-netmod-rfc6020bis-10, chapter 7.20.3.2., regarding *deviate* sub-statements, it says:
>    If the target node has a property defined by an extension, this
>    property can be deviated if the extension allows deviations.

There is no way to model the fact that a given extension supports deviations or not, so the assumption is that it is up to the implementation, not to the model itself.
However, having
```
deviation /some/node {
  deviate add {
    ext:some-extension;
  }
}
```
will break pyang compilation.
This is true with both pyang master branch and the yang 1.1 branch.
Even if that detail was only added in the draft for 1.1, I'd think it also makes sense for 1.0.

Using code similar to this example, when I passed in 4 oid's for my ink jet's color cartridges, I got "no such object currently exists at this oid" for each object.  All error status were 0 so cmdGen.getCmd thought it returned successfully.  Only one of the OID's was incorrect but all 4 returned the same message.  

```
from pysnmp.entity.rfc3413.oneliner import cmdgen

cmdGen = cmdgen.CommandGenerator()

errorIndication, errorStatus, errorIndex, varBinds = cmdGen.getCmd(
    cmdgen.CommunityData('public'),
    cmdgen.UdpTransportTarget(('localhost', 161)),
    '1.3.6.1.2.1.1.1.0',
    '1.3.6.1.2.1.1.6.0'
)

# Check for errors and print out results
if errorIndication:
    print(errorIndication)
else:
    if errorStatus:
        print('%s at %s' % (
            errorStatus.prettyPrint(),
            errorIndex and varBinds[int(errorIndex)-1] or '?'
            )
        )
    else:
        for name, val in varBinds:
            print('%s = %s' % (name.prettyPrint(), val.prettyPrint()))
```

Desired results would be to return the correct value for each oid and return the error message only on the one that actually failed.

